  / Body Planes
  /// Anatomy is often described in planes, referring to two-dimensional sections of the body. A section is a two-dimensional surface of a three-dimensional structure that has been cut. A plane is an imaginary two-dimensional surface that passes through the body.
  model planes
    >>>
      There are three planes commonly referred to in anatomy and medicine:
      1. The __sagittal plane__ is the plane that divides the body or an organ vertically into right and left sides. This passes through the head, spinal cord and navel. If this vertical plane runs directly down the middle of the body, it is called the __midsagittal__ or __median plane__. If it divides the body into unequal right and left sides, it is called a __parasagittal plane__ or less commonly a __longitudinal__ section.
      2. The __frontal plane__ is the plane that divides the body or an organ into an anterior (front) portion and a posterior (rear) portion. The frontal plane is often referred to as a coronal plane. (“Corona” is Latin for “crown.”)
      3. The __transverse plane__ is the plane that divides the body or organ horizontally into upper(cranial) and lower(cordial) portions. Transverse planes produce images referred to as cross sections.
      4. A __radial plane__ is any one of the cross sections that run through a cylindrical shaped portion of the body that are coincident with radii that run from a central point. The midsagittal and midcoronal planes would both be examples of radial planes, but so would all other planes that cross the intersection of these two planes.
